<p>Now, why all this, you'l say?</p>
<p>I Answer, were there no other reason than that, I might (from the second Account, wherein I do only set the Sum, and not recite for what) turn the readilier to the first Account, and see what it is for; this would recompence the trouble: But there is a further and great use thereof to be made in the keeping an Account of Trade, as shall be shewn in due place.</p>
<p>And I do not doubt, but, that if Parents and Superiours imploy their Children or Servants (one at a time, That is, one in one Year, and another in another) in this or the like way of keeping the Accounts of House Expences, or other petty Charges besides; the satisfaction they will have to see how, and which way their Money goes.) They will alto train up their Children to be regular and handy in Accounts of greater Moment.</p>
